videoSnippet.title: World Chess Champion Misses Mate in 1
videoSnippet.description:
#agadmator Vote for my next video series here https://www.youtube.com/user/AGADMATOR/community

Deep Fritz (Computer) vs Vladimir Kramnik
"Deep Sixed" 
Kramnik - Deep Fritz (2006), Bonn GER, rd 2, Nov-27 
Queen's Gambit Accepted: Central. Greco Variation (D20)

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. Nc3 b4 6. Na2 Nf6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bc4 e6 9. Nf3 a5 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. Nc1 Ba6 12. Qe2 h6 13. Be3 Bc4 14. Qc4 Nd7 15. Nb3 Be7 16. Rc1 O-O 17. O-O Rfc8 18. Qe2 c5 19. Nfd2 Qc6 20. Qh5 Qa4 21. Nc5 Nc5 22. dc5 Ne3 23. fe3 Bc5 24. Qf7 Kh8 25. Qf3 Rf8 26. Qe4 Qd7 27. Nb3 Bb6 28. Rfd1 Qf7 29. Rf1 Qa7 30. Rf8 Rf8 31. Nd4 a4 32. Ne6 Be3 33. Kh1 Bc1 34. Nf8 Qe3 35. Qh7#

11/27/2006 â€“ Vladimir Kramnik played another wonderfully profound game, piling the pressure on Deep Fritz on the black side of a Queen's Gambit Accepted, and taking the computer to the edge of defeat. As usual the computer defended tenaciously and by move 34 Fritz had equalised and the game was clearly drawn. And then Kramnik overlooked mate in one!
